                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Fletcher</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Sheriff</pf>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Croft</ln>
                        <fn>David</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Taylor</ln>
                        <fn>David</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Houser</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Armstrong</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>A man who arrived in town and registered as George Woodward, a friend of
                    James Johnston, was caught attempting to sell a stolen horse and buggy. Sheriff
                    Fletcher had purchased the horse for $65 and David Croft bought the buggy when
                    David Taylor grew suspicious about the seller. He inquired in Doylestown and
                    found descriptions of stolen goods that matched that of the horse and buggy.
                    Chief Houser arrested the man and brought him before Judge Armstrong who
                    committed him to jail. Johnston was arrested in Hagerstown, but a woman who had
                    accompanied Woodward escaped.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>

